# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# combined — __rand__, __ror__, __rxor__ across all 10 asyncio subjects
#
# Covers the full matrix: 10 classes x 3 methods = 30 rows.
# __rand__: false for all 10 — reflected bitwise AND is not defined.
# __ror__: false for all 10 — reflected bitwise OR is not defined.
# __rxor__: false for all 10 — reflected bitwise XOR is not defined.
# All 30 values are false.
# asyncio types are designed for coroutine-based concurrency — their entire
#   API surface is expressed through await, async with, async for, and
#   explicit method calls. Neither forward nor reflected bitwise logical
#   operators appear anywhere in the asyncio type hierarchy.
# asyncio.Event note: Event manages a simple boolean flag (set/clear/wait);
#   it does not implement any bitwise data model from either side.
# asyncio.Lock/Condition note: these are mutual-exclusion synchronization
#   objects; bitwise AND, OR, and XOR have no meaning for lock state.
# asyncio.Semaphore/BoundedSemaphore note: the permit counter is a positive
#   integer but is fully encapsulated. No bitwise operator is exposed
#   through any part of the API from either side.
# asyncio.Queue note: Queue is an ordered item store. It does not implement
#   the |, &, or ^ operator from either side; items are managed solely
#   through put()/get() coroutine calls.
# dict.__ror__ distinction: Python 3.9+ dict defines __ror__ for the merge
#   operator (d2 | d1 where d2.__or__ returns NotImplemented). asyncio types
#   are not dicts and do not inherit or implement this protocol.
# This wave continues the unbroken all-false run from wave 656 through
#   wave 665 — ten consecutive waves of 100% false results for asyncio types.
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

